At this point, everything was coming together. The design was solid, the movement system worked, and the software interface gave me real insight into what the launcher was doing.

The final step was simple: wire everything up and attempt the very first full launch.

Below is the video from that first complete test.


https://youtube.com/shorts/7WCyEp3k-Bc

So… it failed.

I couldn’t even get a single launch off—and the reason was a simple design oversight. After spending so much time building the software and pushing toward a “full system” test, I missed one of the most fundamental questions:

Did the football actually have enough clearance to make it through the tube without hitting the side walls?

It didn’t.

That moment was frustrating, but also important. It exposed a blind spot in my process—and that’s exactly what prototyping is supposed to do.

As mentioned before, failure doesn’t mean going backward. It means progress is being made. The system was complex enough now that real limitations were showing themselves.

And progress was made.



